# Table-Driven Tests

Follow [Table-Driven Tests](https://go.dev/wiki/TableDrivenTests).

## Pattern

```go
import (
    "testing"

    "github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp"
    "github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp/cmpopts"
)

func TestParseArgs(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct {
        name  string
        input string
        want  []string
    }{
        {name: "empty", input: "", want: nil},
        {name: "single word", input: "echo", want: []string{"echo"}},
        {name: "quoted", input: `echo "hello world"`, want: []string{"echo", "hello world"}},
    }

    for _, tt := range tests {
        t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            got := ParseArgs(tt.input)
            if diff := cmp.Diff(tt.want, got, cmpopts.EquateEmpty()); diff != "" {
                t.Errorf("ParseArgs(%q) mismatch (-want +got):\n%s", tt.input, diff)
            }
        })
    }
}
```

## Guidelines

- Use a `tests` slice of anonymous structs; each row needs a descriptive `name`.
- Run subtests with `t.Run(tt.name, ...)`.
- Test one function or behavior per test function; add rows for edge cases.
- Compare values with `github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp`; use `cmp.Diff(want, got)` and report the diff as `(-want +got)`.
- Use `cmpopts.EquateEmpty()` when comparing slices or maps where `nil` and empty should match.
- Prefer `t.Errorf` / `t.Fatalf` with context over bare `t.Error`.
- Place tests next to the code they cover (`foo.go` → `foo_test.go`, same package).
